---
<SiteLayout site="28grams" title="Olive Oil Guide: EVOO vs Virgin vs Light" description="Olive oil — EVOO vs virgin vs light, real vs fake, cooking myths." canonical="https://28grams.vip/olive-oil-guide" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero"><h1>Olive Oil Guide: EVOO vs Virgin vs Light</h1><p>Everything you need to know about olive oil varieties and uses.</p></div>

    <h2>Understanding Olive Oil Grades</h2>
    <p>Extra virgin olive oil (EVOO) is unrefined and extracted cold, retaining antioxidants and robust flavor. Virgin olive oil is also unrefined but has slight sensory defects. Refined or 'light' olive oil is treated to remove flaws, resulting in a neutral flavor and higher smoke point.</p>
    <h2>Real vs Fake Olive Oil</h2>
    <p>Authenticity can be an issue with EVOO. Look for certification seals, harvest dates, and dark glass bottles which protect the oil from light degradation.</p>
    <h2>Cooking Myths Debunked</h2>
    <p>It is a common myth that you cannot cook with EVOO. While its smoke point is lower than some refined oils, it is perfectly safe and flavorful for sautéing and baking at moderate temperatures.</p>
